The paper discusses the interplay between dynamical processes and the underlying topologies of complex systems, which is a common theme in network science. It also introduces a new framework for graph signal processing, which is a subfield of network science. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.SI (Social and Information Networks). 

The paper also discusses the modeling of continuous-time dynamical processes, which suggests a connection to numerical analysis and scientific computing (cs.NA). Additionally, the paper mentions the relationship between the Z-Laplacian and nonnegative graph filters, which suggests a connection to information theory (cs.IT) and machine learning (cs.LG). Finally, the two applications discussed in the paper involve wireless communications networking (cs.SY) and structural brain networks (which could fall under cs.NE, cs.BIO, or cs.LG).
